over time? And how do trends in adolescent well-being since the 1970s relate to changes in education, leisure, communities and family life in that time? This unique volume brings together the main findings from the Nuffield Foundation's Changing Adolescence Programme and explores how social change may affect young people's behaviour, mental health and transitions toward adulthood. As well as critiquing research evidence, which will be of interest to a wide academic audience, the book will inform the wider debate on this subject among policy makers and service providers, voluntary organisations and campaign groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAdolescent psychologyzGreat Britain. 0aSocial change. 0aTeenagersxMental health serviceszGreat Britain. 0aTeenagersxSocial conditionsy21st centuryzGreat Britain. 0aTeenagerszGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aYouthxMental health serviceszGreat Britain. 0aYouthzGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAldridge, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollishaw, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaya, Shari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonmall, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalton, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiménez-Nadal, J. Ignacio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, John, econtributor